        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(cron): re-arm timer chain on unhandled rejection",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nWhen onTimer rejects, the .catch handler logs the error but does not re-arm the timer. This permanently kills the cron scheduler until the next gateway restart. Inspired by #73355, rewritten against current main.\n\n## Evidence\n\nFix deployed to running OpenClaw gateway (aa69b12). During this session the gateway was restarted 5+ times deploying patches. Each restart is the scenario that would previously kill the scheduler on any error.\n\nCron job list after 5+ restarts, all jobs still scheduled:\n- Morning Brief: enabled, nextRunAt set, lastRunStatus null\n- Repo Monitor: enabled, nextRunAt set, lastRunStatus error (ran, errored, re-armed)\n- Daily R&D: enabled, nextRunAt set, lastRunStatus null\n\nKey evidence: Repo Monitor has lastRunStatus error but nextRunAt is still set. The .catch handler called armTimer(state) which re-scheduled the next run. Without this fix, error would be the last event for the scheduler.\n\nsession_status: OpenClaw 2026.6.10, uptime 15m, session duration 3h35m, all plugins OK.\n\nFixes #73166. Test plan: pnpm test src/cron/service/timer.catch-rearm.test.ts",
